popup.text: This is a model of a population constrained by natural resources. Experiment with model assumptions and inputs to see what effect they may have on a population and its natural resources over time.

The relationship between a population of people and the natural resources they consume is an important topic for discussion.
Please press the space bar to unfurl the model.
This model shows the relationship between a population of people...
... and the natural resources they consume.
Likewise, they die at a given death rate.
In order to sustain life, the population must consume natural resources.
Each person within the population consumes a certain amount of resources.
These resources regenerate at a regeneration rate.
If natural resources fall too low, however, those resources may lose their ability to regenerate.
Also, if the natural resources per person ratio drops too low...
...there will not be enough resources to consume and the death rate will increase.

One strategy to prevent the natural resources per person ratio from falling too low is to invest in technology that increases the regeneration rate.
To see the effectiveness of this strategy, click the Back Arrow button on the upper left side of the window to return to the Home Page and simulate the model.
